<h2 id="step-by-step-applications">Step-by-step Applications</h2>
<p>These simple models are presented as an introduction to the <strong>GreatMod</strong> usage, showing step by step the base functionalities of the R package, <em>epimod</em>.</p>

<div class="feature__wrapper">

  
    <div class="feature__item">
      <div class="archive__item">
        
          <div class="archive__item-teaser">
            <img src="/assets/images/SIR.png" alt="placeholder image 2" />
            
          </div>
        

        <div class="archive__item-body">
          
            <h2 class="archive__item-title">SIR</h2>
          

          
            <div class="archive__item-excerpt">
              <p>The SIR model is one of the simplest compartmental models, and many models are derivatives of this basic form. The model consists of three compartments: S for the number of susceptible, I for the number of infectious, and R for the number of recovered or deceased.</p>

            </div>
          

          
            <p><a href="https://github.com/qBioTurin/SIR" class="btn btn--primary">Read More</a></p>
          
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  
    <div class="feature__item">
      <div class="archive__item">
        
          <div class="archive__item-teaser">
            <img src="/assets/images/lotkaV.png" alt="placeholder image 2" />
            
          </div>
        

        <div class="archive__item-body">
          
            <h2 class="archive__item-title">Lotka Volterra</h2>
          

          
            <div class="archive__item-excerpt">
              <p>The Lotka–Volterra equations, also known as the predator–prey equations, are a pair of first-order nonlinear differential equations, frequently used to describe the dynamics of biological systems in which two species interact, one as a predator and the other as prey.</p>

            </div>
          

          
            <p><a href="https://github.com/qBioTurin/Lotka-Volterra" class="btn btn--primary">Read More</a></p>
          
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  

</div>

